`getChildren` returns direct children only. `enumerateChildren` can search recursively.

**`getChildren()`:**
```typescript
const directChildren: cc.Node[] = parent.getChildren();
// Returns only immediate children, not grandchildren
```

**`enumerateChildren(name, callback)`:**
```typescript
// Search direct children named 'enemy'
parent.enumerateChildren('enemy', (node) => {
    cc.log('Found: ' + node.getName());
    return false; // continue
});

// Search ALL descendants with '//' prefix
parent.enumerateChildren('//enemy', (node) => {
    // Finds 'enemy' at any depth in the subtree
    return false;
});
```

Use `getChildren()` when you know the node is a direct child. Use `enumerateChildren` with `//` prefix for deep searches in complex hierarchies.

Use `cc.director.setAnimationInterval` with the interval in seconds:

```typescript
// Set to 60 FPS (default)
cc.director.setAnimationInterval(1 / 60);

// Set to 30 FPS (for battery saving)
cc.director.setAnimationInterval(1 / 30);

// Get current interval
const interval = cc.director.getAnimationInterval(); // e.g., 0.01667 for 60fps
const targetFPS = Math.round(1 / interval);
cc.log('Target FPS:', targetFPS);

// Get actual frame time
const dt = cc.director.getDeltaTime();         // seconds since last frame
const spf = cc.director.getSecondsPerFrame(); // actual seconds per frame
const totalFrames = cc.director.getTotalFrames();
cc.log('Actual FPS:', Math.round(1 / spf));
```

The parameter is the **interval between frames in seconds**, not the FPS value. So 60 FPS = 1/60, 30 FPS = 1/30.

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this event dispatch code:

```typescript
class PowerUpManager {
    collectPowerUp(type: string): void {
        const listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener('powerup:collected', (event) => {
            const data = event.getUserData<{ type: string }>();
            this.applyPowerUp(data.type);
        });
        cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent('powerup:collected', { type: type });
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is that a **new listener is registered every time** `collectPowerUp` is called, but the dispatch also happens each time. This means:
- First call: 1 listener fires
- Second call: 2 listeners fire (old + new)
- Third call: 3 listeners fire
- And so on — exponential duplication.

The listener registration should be separate from the dispatch:

```typescript
class PowerUpManager {
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;

    init(): void {
        // Register listener ONCE
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener(
            'powerup:collected',
            (event: cc.Event) => {
                const data = event.getUserData<{ type: string }>();
                this.applyPowerUp(data.type);
            }
        );
    }

    collectPowerUp(type: string): void {
        // Only dispatch
        cc.eventManager.dispatchCustomEvent('powerup:collected', { type: type });
    }

    applyPowerUp(type: string): void {
        cc.log('Applying power-up:', type);
    }

    destroy(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
    }
}
```

Rule of thumb: register listeners during initialization (`init`/`onEnter`), dispatch during gameplay, and clean up during teardown (`destroy`/`onExit`).

