this.addChild(label);
label.setString('This is a much longer string');
const width = label.getContentSize().width; // still shows 'Short' width
```

output:
The bug is that the label's content size isn't updated immediately after `setString`. The layout recalculation happens on the next frame.

**Fix:** Call `updateContent()` to force immediate recalculation:

```typescript
const label = cc.Label.createWithSystemFont('Short', 'Arial', 20);
this.addChild(label);
label.setString('This is a much longer string');
label.updateContent(); // force recalculate
const width = label.getContentSize().width; // correct width
```

Create a HUD layout and schedule updates for dynamic values:

```typescript
class GameHUD extends cc.Node {
    private hpBar: ccui.LoadingBar;
    private mpBar: ccui.LoadingBar;
    private scoreLabel: ccui.Text;
    private timerLabel: ccui.Text;
    private timeLeft: number = 120;

    init(): boolean {
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        const panel = new ccui.Layout();
        panel.setSize(cc.size(winSize.width, 60));
        panel.setPosition(0, winSize.height - 60);
        panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
        panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(20, 20, 30));
        panel.setBackGroundColorOpacity(200);
        this.addChild(panel);

        this.hpBar = new ccui.LoadingBar('hp_bar.png', 100);
        this.hpBar.setPosition(100, 40);
        panel.addChild(this.hpBar);

        this.mpBar = new ccui.LoadingBar('mp_bar.png', 100);
        this.mpBar.setPosition(100, 15);
        panel.addChild(this.mpBar);

        this.scoreLabel = new ccui.Text('0', 'Arial', 22);
        this.scoreLabel.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, 30);
        panel.addChild(this.scoreLabel);

        this.timerLabel = new ccui.Text('2:00', 'Arial', 20);
        this.timerLabel.setPosition(winSize.width - 50, 30);
        panel.addChild(this.timerLabel);

        this.schedule(this.updateTimer, 1.0);
        return true;
    }

    updateTimer(dt: number): void {
        this.timeLeft--;
        const m = Math.floor(this.timeLeft / 60);
        const s = this.timeLeft % 60;
        this.timerLabel.setString(m + ':' + (s < 10 ? '0' : '') + s);
        if (this.timeLeft <= 0) {
            this.unschedule(this.updateTimer);
        }
    }

    setHP(pct: number): void { this.hpBar.setPercent(pct); }
    setMP(pct: number): void { this.mpBar.setPercent(pct); }
    setScore(val: number): void { this.scoreLabel.setString(String(val)); }
}
```

instruction:
Review this code and identify problems:

```typescript
class UILayer extends cc.Layer {
    private panels: cc.LayerColor[] = [];

    addPanel(color: cc.Color): void {
        const panel = new cc.LayerColor(color, 200, 150);
        this.panels.push(panel);
    }

    showPanel(index: number): void {
        this.panels[index].setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

output:
Issues found:

1. **Panels never added to display tree**: `addPanel` creates a `cc.LayerColor` and stores it in the array, but never calls `this.addChild(panel)`. The panels will never be rendered.

2. **No bounds checking**: `showPanel` accesses `this.panels[index]` without checking if the index is valid.

3. **No way to hide other panels**: `showPanel` makes one visible but doesn't hide the others.

**Fixed code:**
```typescript
class UILayer extends cc.Layer {
    private panels: cc.LayerColor[] = [];

    addPanel(color: cc.Color): void {
        const panel = new cc.LayerColor(color, 200, 150);
        panel.setVisible(false);
        this.addChild(panel);  // Add to display tree
        this.panels.push(panel);
    }

    showPanel(index: number): void {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.panels.length) {
            cc.log('Invalid panel index: ' + index);
            return;
        }
        for (let i = 0; i < this.panels.length; i++) {
            this.panels[i].setVisible(i === index);
        }
    }

    hideAllPanels(): void {
        for (const panel of this.panels) {
            panel.setVisible(false);
        }
    }
}
```

Panels are now added as children, bounds are checked, and showing one panel hides the others.

`getSafeAreaRect` returns the safe area rectangle on devices with notches or rounded corners:

```typescript
const safeRect: cc.Rect = cc.director.getSafeAreaRect();
// safeRect.x, safeRect.y — origin of safe area
// safeRect.width, safeRect.height — safe area dimensions
```

Use it for UI positioning:
```typescript
class SafeAreaUI extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        const safeRect = cc.director.getSafeAreaRect();
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();

        // Calculate insets
        const insetLeft = safeRect.x;
        const insetBottom = safeRect.y;
        const insetRight = winSize.width - (safeRect.x + safeRect.width);
        const insetTop = winSize.height - (safeRect.y + safeRect.height);

        cc.log('Safe insets — L:', insetLeft, 'R:', insetRight,
               'T:', insetTop, 'B:', insetBottom);

        // Position HUD within safe area
        const scoreLabel = new cc.LabelTTF('Score: 0', 'Arial', 20);
        scoreLabel.setPosition(
            safeRect.x + safeRect.width - 80,
            safeRect.y + safeRect.height - 30
        );
        this.addChild(scoreLabel);

        // Health bar at safe bottom-left
        const healthBar = new cc.Sprite('res/ui/health.png');
        healthBar.setPosition(
            safeRect.x + 100,
            safeRect.y + 30
        );
        this.addChild(healthBar);
    }
}
```

On devices without notches, the safe area equals the full window size.

Use `convertToGL` and `convertToUI` for coordinate system conversion:

```typescript
// UI coordinates (origin top-left, Y down) → GL coordinates (origin bottom-left, Y up)
const glPoint = cc.director.convertToGL(uiPoint: cc.Point): cc.Point

// GL coordinates → UI coordinates
const uiPoint = cc.director.convertToUI(glPoint: cc.Point): cc.Point
```

Examples:
```typescript
// Convert a screen tap (UI space) to game world (GL space)
const screenTap = cc.p(100, 50);  // top-left origin
const worldPos = cc.director.convertToGL(screenTap);
cc.log('World position:', worldPos.x, worldPos.y);

// Convert a game object position to screen coordinates
const spritePos = sprite.getPosition();
const screenPos = cc.director.convertToUI(spritePos);
cc.log('Screen position:', screenPos.x, screenPos.y);

// Useful for interfacing with HTML DOM elements in H5
function positionHtmlElement(element: HTMLElement, gamePos: cc.Point): void {
    const uiPos = cc.director.convertToUI(gamePos);
    element.style.left = uiPos.x + 'px';
    element.style.top = uiPos.y + 'px';
}
```

Note: In Cocos2d-x, game logic typically uses GL coordinates. UI coordinates are mainly needed when interfacing with browser DOM elements or platform-specific UI.

`cc.sys.capabilities` is an object indicating what input methods are available:

