Use `scheduleUpdateForTarget` to control the order in which nodes receive `update` calls:

```typescript
const scheduler = cc.director.getScheduler();

// Lower priority number = called first
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    physicsManager,  // target (must implement update(dt))
    -10,             // priority: runs before default (0)
    false            // not paused
);

scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    gameLogic,
    0,               // default priority
    false
);

scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(
    renderManager,
    10,              // runs after default
    false
);
```

This ensures a deterministic update order:
1. Physics (priority -10) — updates positions
2. Game logic (priority 0) — checks collisions, applies rules
3. Render (priority 10) — updates visual state

Unschedule:
```typescript
scheduler.unscheduleUpdateForTarget(physicsManager);
```

The targets must implement an `update(dt: number)` method:
```typescript
class PhysicsManager extends cc.Class {
    update(dt: number): void {
        // Physics step
    }
}
```

Note: `node.scheduleUpdate()` uses priority 0 by default. Use the scheduler directly when you need explicit ordering.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The node doesn't return to its original position after a moveBy sequence:

```typescript
const shake = cc.sequence(
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(10, 0)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(-10, 0)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(0, 10)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(0, -10))
);
node.runAction(cc.repeat(shake, 5));
// node ends up offset from original position
```

output:
The moveBy values cancel out perfectly (10-10 = 0, 10-10 = 0), so this SHOULD return to origin. The actual bug might be floating point accumulation over 5 repeats.

**Fix:** Add a final position reset:

```typescript
const originalPos = node.getPosition();
const shake = cc.sequence(
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(10, 0)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(-10, 0)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(0, 10)),
    cc.moveBy(0.05, cc.p(0, -10))
);
node.runAction(cc.sequence(
    cc.repeat(shake, 5),
    cc.moveTo(0.05, originalPos) // snap back to exact position
));
```

Check `cc.sys.capabilities.keyboard` before registering:

```typescript
class InputManager {
    private _keyListener: cc.EventListener | null = null;

    setupKeyboard(node: cc.Node): boolean {
        if (!cc.sys.capabilities.keyboard) {
            cc.log('Keyboard not available on this platform');
            return false;
        }

        this._keyListener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD,
            onKeyPressed: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this.handleKeyDown(keyCode);
            },
            onKeyReleased: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
                this.handleKeyUp(keyCode);
            }
        }, node);

        cc.log('Keyboard input enabled');
        return true;
    }

    cleanup(): void {
        if (this._keyListener) {
            cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._keyListener);
            this._keyListener = null;
        }
    }
}

// In your layer:
onEnter(): void {
    super.onEnter();
    const input = new InputManager();
    if (!input.setupKeyboard(this)) {
        // Keyboard not available — show virtual controls
        this.createVirtualDPad();
    }
}
```

`cc.sys.capabilities.keyboard` is `true` on desktop platforms (native and browser) and `false` on mobile platforms (unless an external keyboard is connected, which isn't detected).

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this touch listener code:

```typescript
class ButtonLayer extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => {
                cc.log('Touch started');
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => {
                cc.log('Button tapped!');
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is that `onTouchBegan` does not return `true`. In Cocos2d-x, `onTouchBegan` must return `true` to claim the touch; otherwise `onTouchMoved`, `onTouchEnded`, and `onTouchCancelled` will never fire.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class ButtonLayer extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                cc.log('Touch started');
                return true; // FIX: must return true to receive onTouchEnded
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                cc.log('Button tapped!');
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

Without `return true`, the touch is not claimed and all subsequent callbacks for that touch are skipped. This is one of the most common bugs with Cocos2d-x touch handling.

