Use `cc.BlendFunc` with `cc.ONE` as the source factor:

```typescript
// Premultiplied alpha: src=ONE, dst=ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA
sprite.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.ONE, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA));
```

Premultiplied alpha is used when textures have their RGB channels pre-multiplied by the alpha value. This is common with:
- PVR textures on iOS
- Textures processed by TexturePacker with "premultiply alpha" enabled
- PNG files from certain tools

Comparison of common blend modes:
```typescript
// Normal alpha blend (non-premultiplied textures)
sprite.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA));

// Premultiplied alpha
sprite.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.ONE, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA));

// Additive blend (for glow/fire effects)
sprite.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.ONE, cc.ONE));

// Additive with alpha (softer glow)
sprite.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE));
```

Using the wrong blend mode causes visual artifacts — dark halos around sprites (wrong alpha) or overly bright/dim sprites (wrong premultiply assumption).

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this audio settings code:

```typescript
class AudioSettings {
    private musicVol: number = 0.7;
    private sfxVol: number = 0.8;

    setMusicVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.musicVol = vol;
    }

    setSfxVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.sfxVol = vol;
    }

    applySettings(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);
    }
}

const settings = new AudioSettings();
settings.setMusicVolume(0.3);
// Music doesn't change volume!
```

output:
The bug is that `setMusicVolume` only stores the value locally but never calls `cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume`. The user would need to also call `applySettings()`, which is easy to forget.

**Fixed code:**
```typescript
class AudioSettings {
    private musicVol: number = 0.7;
    private sfxVol: number = 0.8;

    setMusicVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.musicVol = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, vol));
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);  // Apply immediately
    }

    setSfxVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.sfxVol = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, vol));
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);  // Apply immediately
    }

    applySettings(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);
    }
}

const settings = new AudioSettings();
settings.setMusicVolume(0.3);  // Now works immediately
```

The fix applies the volume to `cc.audioEngine` immediately when set, in addition to storing it. Also adds clamping to keep values in 0–1 range. `applySettings` is still useful for restoring saved settings on startup.

