`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)` switches to layer at index `n` AND releases (frees memory of) the currently displayed layer:

```typescript
const mainLayer = new cc.Layer();
const tutorialLayer = new cc.Layer();
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(mainLayer, tutorialLayer);
scene.addChild(multiplex);

// Show tutorial first
multiplex.switchTo(1);

// Switch to main and release tutorial (one-time screen)
multiplex.switchToAndReleaseMe(0);
// tutorialLayer is now released and cannot be switched back to
```

**`switchTo(n)`** — shows layer `n`, hides current. The current layer remains in memory and can be switched back to later.

**`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)`** — shows layer `n`, removes AND releases the current layer. Use this when the current layer won't be needed again (e.g., one-time tutorial, loading screen).

Use `switchTo` for screens you revisit (main menu, settings). Use `switchToAndReleaseMe` for one-time screens to save memory.

instruction:
Fix the bug in this code that adds sprites to a batch node:

```typescript
const batch = new cc.SpriteBatchNode('res/atlas_a.png', 100);
this.addChild(batch);

const s1 = new cc.Sprite('res/hero.png'); // from atlas_a
const s2 = new cc.Sprite('res/enemy.png'); // from a DIFFERENT texture!
batch.addChild(s1);
batch.addChild(s2);
```

output:
The bug is that `s2` uses a different texture (`res/enemy.png`) than the batch node (`res/atlas_a.png`). All sprites in a `cc.SpriteBatchNode` must share the same texture. Adding a sprite with a different texture will cause rendering errors or crashes.

Fixed code:
```typescript
const batch = new cc.SpriteBatchNode('res/atlas_a.png', 100);
this.addChild(batch);

// Both sprites must use frames from the same atlas texture
cc.spriteFrameCache.addSpriteFrames('res/atlas_a.plist', 'res/atlas_a.png');

const s1 = new cc.Sprite(cc.spriteFrameCache.getSpriteFrame('hero.png'));
const s2 = new cc.Sprite(cc.spriteFrameCache.getSpriteFrame('enemy.png'));
batch.addChild(s1);
batch.addChild(s2);
```

Both `hero.png` and `enemy.png` must be frames within the `atlas_a` spritesheet. If they're from different textures, use separate batch nodes or add them directly to the layer.

