`pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority` pauses only targets at or above a given priority:

```typescript
scheduler.pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority(minPriority: number): void
```

This lets you pause gameplay while keeping critical systems running:

```typescript
const scheduler = cc.director.getScheduler();

// Priority scheme:
// -100: System (always runs)
// -50: UI (runs during pause)
// 0: Gameplay (paused during pause)
// 50: VFX (paused during pause)

// Register with explicit priorities
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(systemManager, -100, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(uiManager, -50, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(gameplayManager, 0, false);
scheduler.scheduleUpdateForTarget(vfxManager, 50, false);

// Pause only gameplay and VFX (priority >= 0)
scheduler.pauseAllTargetsWithMinPriority(0);
// systemManager and uiManager keep running

// Resume all
scheduler.resumeTargets([gameplayManager, vfxManager]);
```

This is more surgical than `cc.director.pause()` which stops everything. Use it when you need the UI to remain interactive during a game pause.

