```

Iterate through nodes and test each one:

```typescript
const interactiveNodes: cc.Node[] = [node1, node2, node3];

cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
        for (const node of interactiveNodes) {
            if (!node.isVisible()) continue;
            const localPt = node.convertTouchToNodeSpace(touch);
            const rect = cc.rect(0, 0, node.width, node.height);
            if (cc.rectContainsPoint(rect, localPt)) {
                cc.log('Tapped: ' + node.getName());
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}, this);
```

For many nodes, use `getBoundingBoxToWorld()` for a faster pre-check before converting coordinates:
```typescript
const worldRect = node.getBoundingBoxToWorld();
const touchLoc = touch.getLocation();
if (cc.rectContainsPoint(worldRect, touchLoc)) { /* hit */ }
```

Both create an identical `cc.DrawNode` instance. The difference is stylistic:

- **`new cc.DrawNode()`** — Standard JS constructor syntax. Preferred in TypeScript codebases.
- **`cc.DrawNode.create()`** — Static factory method, following Cocos2d-x C++ conventions. Common in older JS code and examples ported from C++.

```typescript
// Both are equivalent:
const draw1 = new cc.DrawNode();
const draw2 = cc.DrawNode.create();
```

Neither has a performance advantage. Use whichever matches your project's existing style. In TypeScript projects, `new cc.DrawNode()` is more idiomatic. In legacy Cocos2d-x JS projects that follow the C++ API style, `cc.DrawNode.create()` is more common.

Both return a `cc.DrawNode` which extends `cc.Node`, so you can use all `cc.Node` methods like `setPosition`, `setScale`, etc.

Use removeAllActionsFromTarget to stop and remove every action running on a node:

```typescript
const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(mySprite, true);
```

The second param (forceDelete) when true removes even locked actions. Common cleanup pattern:

```typescript
class Enemy extends cc.Sprite {
    destroy(): void {
        const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(this, true);
        this.removeFromParent();
    }
}

// Batch cleanup
function cleanupAll(nodes: cc.Node[]): void {
    const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
    for (const node of nodes) {
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(node, true);
        node.removeFromParent();
    }
}
```

This is the ActionManager equivalent of `node.stopAllActions()`. Use the manager directly when you need to clean up nodes you do not have direct references to.

