Fix the bug. The action is reused on two nodes but only one works:

```typescript
const fade = cc.fadeOut(0.5);
nodeA.runAction(fade);
nodeB.runAction(fade);
```

output:
The bug is that an action instance can only be used on one node at a time. Running the same action on two nodes causes undefined behavior — typically only the second node is animated.

**Fix:** Clone the action:

```typescript
const fade = cc.fadeOut(0.5);
nodeA.runAction(fade);
nodeB.runAction(fade.clone());
```

Or create separate instances:
```typescript
nodeA.runAction(cc.fadeOut(0.5));
nodeB.runAction(cc.fadeOut(0.5));
```

