`cc.sys.garbageCollect()` forces JavaScript garbage collection on native (JSB) platforms:

```typescript
cc.sys.garbageCollect(): void  // JSB only, no-op on H5
```

Use it after large memory operations like scene transitions:

```typescript
class SceneTransitionHelper {
    static switchScene(newScene: cc.Scene): void {
        // Purge caches first
        cc.director.purgeCachedData();

        // Force GC on native platforms
        if (cc.sys.isNative) {
            cc.sys.garbageCollect();
        }

        // Run the new scene
        cc.director.runScene(newScene);
    }
}

// After loading large assets
cc.loader.load(['res/large_atlas.png', 'res/level_data.json'], (err) => {
    if (err) return;
    // Process data...

    // Release temporary references and collect
    if (cc.sys.isNative) {
        cc.sys.garbageCollect();
    }
});
```

**When to use:**
- After scene transitions with `purgeCachedData()`
- After releasing large textures or audio
- When memory warnings are received

**When NOT to use:**
- Every frame (causes stuttering)
- During gameplay (GC pauses can cause frame drops)

Related JSB-only methods:
- `cc.sys.dumpRoot()` — debug dump of root object
- `cc.sys.restartVM()` — restart the JS virtual machine

ScrollView fires these event types through its `addEventListener` callback:

```typescript
sv.addEventListener((sender, type) => {
    switch (type) {
        // Scroll reached edges:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_TOP:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_LEFT:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_RIGHT:

        // Actively scrolling:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLLING:

        // Bounce events (when bounce is enabled):
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_TOP:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_BOTTOM:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_LEFT:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_RIGHT:
    }
}, this);
```

Common use cases:
- `EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM` — infinite scroll / load more
- `EVENT_SCROLLING` — update UI during scroll (parallax, headers)
- `EVENT_BOUNCE_*` — visual feedback on overscroll

Note: These events use `addEventListener`, not `addTouchEventListener`.

The `drawLineToCenter` parameter is a boolean that, when `true`, draws a line from a point on the circumference to the center of the circle.

```typescript
draw.drawCircle(center, radius, angle, segments, drawLineToCenter, lineWidth, color)
```

- When `false`: Only the circle outline is drawn.
- When `true`: A radius line is also drawn from the point at `angle` to the center.

Example:
```typescript
const draw = new cc.DrawNode();
this.addChild(draw);

// Without radius line
draw.drawCircle(cc.p(100, 160), 50, 0, 32, false, 2, cc.color(255, 255, 0, 255));

// With radius line — useful for showing rotation
draw.drawCircle(cc.p(300, 160), 50, Math.PI / 4, 32, true, 2, cc.color(0, 255, 0, 255));
```

**Use cases:**
- Visualizing rotation direction (the radius line acts like a clock hand)
- Debug display for physics bodies with angular velocity
- Showing the `angle` parameter visually during development

The line starts from `center + radius` at the given `angle` and goes to `center`.

