Use custom events to decouple nodes:

```typescript
// Define event names as constants
const EVENTS = {
    PLAYER_DIED: 'player_died',
    SCORE_CHANGED: 'score_changed',
};

// In PlayerNode - dispatch event
class PlayerNode extends cc.Sprite {
    die(): void {
        const event = new cc.EventCustom(EVENTS.PLAYER_DIED);
        event.setUserData({ position: this.getPosition() });
        cc.eventManager.dispatchEvent(event);
        this.removeFromParent(true);
    }
}

// In HUDNode - listen for event
class HUDNode extends cc.Node {
    private listener: cc.EventListener;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this.listener = cc.eventManager.addCustomListener(EVENTS.PLAYER_DIED, (event) => {
            const data = event.getUserData();
            cc.log('Player died at: ' + data.position.x);
            this.showGameOver();
        });
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this.listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

`cc.director.purgeCachedData()` clears all cached textures, sprite frames, and animations:

```typescript
cc.director.purgeCachedData(): void
```

Use it during scene transitions to free memory:

```typescript
class SceneTransition {
    static switchTo(newScene: cc.Scene, purge: boolean = true): void {
        if (purge) {
            // Release all cached resources
            cc.director.purgeCachedData();
            cc.log('Cached data purged');
        }
        cc.director.runScene(new cc.TransitionFade(0.5, newScene));
    }
}

// Purge during heavy scene transitions
SceneTransition.switchTo(new GameScene(), true);

// Don't purge for lightweight overlays
SceneTransition.switchTo(new SettingsScene(), false);
```

This clears:
- `cc.textureCache` — all loaded textures
- `cc.spriteFrameCache` — all sprite frame definitions
- `cc.animationCache` — all animation data

After purging, any resources needed by the new scene must be reloaded. Use selectively — purging everything before a scene that shares assets with the current scene will cause unnecessary reloading.

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this DrawNode animation loop:

```typescript
class PulsingCircle extends cc.Layer {
    private _draw: cc.DrawNode;
    private _radius: number = 10;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._draw = new cc.DrawNode();
        this.addChild(this._draw);
        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        this._radius += dt * 50;
        if (this._radius > 100) this._radius = 10;
        this._draw.drawCircle(
            cc.p(240, 160), this._radius, 0, 32, false, 2,
            cc.color(255, 100, 0, 255)
        );
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is that `clear()` is never called before drawing. Each frame adds a new circle on top of the previous ones, so you see all the circles stacking up rather than an animated pulsing effect.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class PulsingCircle extends cc.Layer {
    private _draw: cc.DrawNode;
    private _radius: number = 10;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._draw = new cc.DrawNode();
        this.addChild(this._draw);
        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        this._radius += dt * 50;
        if (this._radius > 100) this._radius = 10;
        this._draw.clear();  // <-- must clear before redrawing
        this._draw.drawCircle(
            cc.p(240, 160), this._radius, 0, 32, false, 2,
            cc.color(255, 100, 0, 255)
        );
    }
}
```

Always call `draw.clear()` at the start of `update()` when doing per-frame drawing.

Use `enumerateChildren` with a name pattern and callback:

```typescript
// Find all children named 'enemy'
parent.enumerateChildren('enemy', (node) => {
    cc.log('Found: ' + node.getName());
    return false; // continue searching (return true to stop)
});

// Find first match
let found: cc.Node | null = null;
parent.enumerateChildren('player', (node) => {
    found = node;
    return true; // stop after first match
});

// Use path pattern (recursive)
parent.enumerateChildren('//enemy', (node) => {
    // finds 'enemy' at any depth
    return false;
});
```

Return `true` from the callback to stop enumeration early, `false` to continue.

instruction:
Review this code for best practices:

```typescript
class Bullet extends cc.Sprite {
    fire(target: cc.Point): void {
        const dist = cc.pDistance(this.getPosition(), target);
        const duration = dist / 500;
        this.runAction(cc.sequence(
            cc.moveTo(duration, target),
            cc.callFunc(() => this.onHit()),
            cc.removeSelf()
        ));
    }
    onHit(): void { /* damage logic */ }
}
```

output:
This code is **well-structured** and follows good patterns:
- Speed-based duration calculation (consistent speed regardless of distance)
- Clean sequence: move → callback → cleanup
- Self-contained behavior

Minor suggestions:
1. Add a rotation to face the target direction
2. Guard against zero distance

```typescript
class Bullet extends cc.Sprite {
    fire(target: cc.Point): void {
        const pos = this.getPosition();
        const dist = cc.pDistance(pos, target);
        if (dist < 1) return; // guard

        // Face target
        const angle = -Math.atan2(target.y - pos.y, target.x - pos.x) * 180 / Math.PI;
        this.setRotation(angle);

        const duration = dist / 500;
        this.runAction(cc.sequence(
            cc.moveTo(duration, target),
            cc.callFunc(() => this.onHit()),
            cc.removeSelf()
        ));
    }
    onHit(): void { /* damage logic */ }
}
```

