Use a sine wave in the update function:

```typescript
class BobbingNode extends cc.Sprite {
    private baseY: number = 0;
    private elapsed: number = 0;
    private amplitude: number = 20;
    private frequency: number = 2;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this.baseY = this.y;
        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        this.elapsed += dt;
        this.y = this.baseY + Math.sin(this.elapsed * this.frequency * Math.PI * 2) * this.amplitude;
    }

    onExit(): void {
        this.unscheduleUpdate();
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

`cc.EventTouch.getTouches()` returns an array of all active `cc.Touch` objects associated with the event:

```typescript
event.getTouches(): cc.Touch[]
```

This is available on `cc.EventTouch` instances, typically accessed in `TOUCH_ALL_AT_ONCE` callbacks:

```typescript
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ALL_AT_ONCE,
    onTouchesBegan: (touches: cc.Touch[], event: cc.Event): void => {
        cc.log('Number of touches:', touches.length);
        for (const touch of touches) {
            cc.log('Touch ID:', touch.getID(), 'at', touch.getLocationX(), touch.getLocationY());
        }
    },
    onTouchesMoved: (touches: cc.Touch[], event: cc.Event): void => {
        if (touches.length === 2) {
            // Two-finger gesture
            const t1 = touches[0].getLocation();
            const t2 = touches[1].getLocation();
            const midpoint = cc.pMidpoint(t1, t2);
            cc.log('Gesture center:', midpoint.x, midpoint.y);
        }
    }
}, this);
```

`cc.EventTouch.MAX_TOUCHES` gives the maximum number of simultaneous touches supported by the platform.

```typescript
type FrameEventHandler = (bone: ccs.Bone, eventName: string, origFrame: number, curFrame: number) => void;
type MovementEventHandler = (armature: ccs.Armature, type: number, id: string) => void;

class ArmatureEventDispatcher {
    private _frameHandlers: Map<string, FrameEventHandler[]> = new Map();
    private _movementHandlers: MovementEventHandler[] = [];

    constructor(armature: ccs.Armature) {
        armature.animation.setFrameEventCallFunc(
            (bone, name, orig, cur) => this.dispatchFrame(bone, name, orig, cur)
        );
        armature.animation.setMovementEventCallFunc(
            (arm, type, id) => this.dispatchMovement(arm, type, id)
        );
    }

    onFrameEvent(eventName: string, handler: FrameEventHandler): void {
        if (!this._frameHandlers.has(eventName)) {
            this._frameHandlers.set(eventName, []);
        }
        this._frameHandlers.get(eventName)!.push(handler);
    }

    onMovementEvent(handler: MovementEventHandler): void {
        this._movementHandlers.push(handler);
    }

    offFrameEvent(eventName: string, handler: FrameEventHandler): void {
        const handlers = this._frameHandlers.get(eventName);
        if (!handlers) return;
        const idx = handlers.indexOf(handler);
        if (idx !== -1) handlers.splice(idx, 1);
    }

    private dispatchFrame(bone: ccs.Bone, name: string, orig: number, cur: number): void {
        const handlers = this._frameHandlers.get(name);
        if (!handlers) return;
        for (const h of handlers) {
            h(bone, name, orig, cur);
        }
    }

    private dispatchMovement(arm: ccs.Armature, type: number, id: string): void {
        for (const h of this._movementHandlers) {
            h(arm, type, id);
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
const dispatcher = new ArmatureEventDispatcher(armature);

dispatcher.onFrameEvent('footstep', (bone) => {
    cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/sfx_step.mp3');
});

dispatcher.onFrameEvent('attack_hit', (bone) => {
    const pos = bone.getWorldPosition();
    spawnHitEffect(pos);
});

dispatcher.onMovementEvent((arm, type, id) => {
    if (type === ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE) {
        cc.log('Finished:', id);
    }
});
```

instruction:
Review this platform detection code for potential issues:

```typescript
class PlatformHelper {
    static isIOS(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.IPHONE;
    }

    static isAndroid(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.os === 'android';
    }

    static isBrowser(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.browserType !== null;
    }
}
```

output:
Issues found:

**Issue 1: `isIOS()` misses iPad.** Only checks `IPHONE` (4) but not `IPAD` (5). iPad users won't be detected as iOS.

**Issue 2: `isAndroid()` uses wrong string.** `cc.sys.os` returns `'Android'` (capital A), not `'android'`. Should use `cc.sys.OS_ANDROID` constant.

**Issue 3: `isBrowser()` is fragile.** Checking `browserType !== null` works but doesn't account for `undefined`. The `isNative` flag is more reliable.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class PlatformHelper {
    static isIOS(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.IPHONE ||
               cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.IPAD;
    }

    static isAndroid(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.os === cc.sys.OS_ANDROID; // 'Android'
    }

    static isBrowser(): boolean {
        return !cc.sys.isNative; // most reliable check
    }

    static isMobileBrowser(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.MOBILE_BROWSER;
    }

    static isDesktopBrowser(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.DESKTOP_BROWSER;
    }

    static isNativeDesktop(): boolean {
        return cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.WIN32 ||
               cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.MACOS ||
               cc.sys.platform === cc.sys.LINUX;
    }
}
```

Key: always use the provided constants (`cc.sys.OS_ANDROID`, `cc.sys.IPAD`, etc.) instead of raw strings or incomplete checks.

Create a `cc.LayerMultiplex` with multiple layers, then use `switchTo` to show one at a time:

```typescript
const mainLayer = new cc.Layer();
const settingsLayer = new cc.Layer();
const inventoryLayer = new cc.Layer();

// Create multiplex with initial layers
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(mainLayer, settingsLayer, inventoryLayer);
scene.addChild(multiplex);

// Show main (index 0) — this is the default
multiplex.switchTo(0);

// Switch to settings (index 1)
multiplex.switchTo(1);

// Switch to inventory (index 2)
multiplex.switchTo(2);

// Add a new layer dynamically
const shopLayer = new cc.Layer();
multiplex.addLayer(shopLayer);
multiplex.switchTo(3);  // switch to shop
```

`switchTo(n)` removes the currently visible layer and shows layer at index `n`. Only one layer is visible and active at a time. Use `switchToAndReleaseMe(n)` if you want to also release the current layer's memory.

Ease functions return objects used with the `.easing()` method:

```typescript
// Rate-based easing
declare function cc.easeIn(rate: number): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeOut(rate: number): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeInOut(rate: number): cc.ActionEase;

// Specific curve easings (no parameters)
declare function cc.easeSineIn(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeSineOut(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeSineInOut(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeBackIn(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeBackOut(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeBounceIn(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeBounceOut(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeExponentialIn(): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeExponentialOut(): cc.ActionEase;

// Parameterized easings
declare function cc.easeElasticIn(period?: number): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeElasticOut(period?: number): cc.ActionEase;
declare function cc.easeBezierAction(p0: number, p1: number, p2: number, p3: number): cc.ActionEase;
