output:
```typescript
class Minimap {
    private container: cc.LayerColor;
    private dots: cc.LayerColor[] = [];
    private mapScale: number;
    private mapWidth: number;
    private mapHeight: number;

    private static readonly DOT_SIZE = 4;
    private static readonly BG_ALPHA = 180;

    constructor(width: number, height: number, worldWidth: number) {
        this.mapWidth = width;
        this.mapHeight = height;
        this.mapScale = width / worldWidth;

        this.container = new cc.LayerColor(
            cc.color(0, 0, 0, Minimap.BG_ALPHA),
            width, height
        );
    }

    getNode(): cc.LayerColor {
        return this.container;
    }

    addEntity(worldX: number, worldY: number, color: cc.Color): number {
        const dot = new cc.LayerColor(
            color,
            Minimap.DOT_SIZE, Minimap.DOT_SIZE
        );
        const mapX = worldX * this.mapScale;
        const mapY = worldY * this.mapScale;
        dot.setPosition(
            Math.min(mapX, this.mapWidth - Minimap.DOT_SIZE),
            Math.min(mapY, this.mapHeight - Minimap.DOT_SIZE)
        );
        this.container.addChild(dot, 1);
        this.dots.push(dot);
        return this.dots.length - 1;
    }

    updateEntity(index: number, worldX: number, worldY: number): void {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.dots.length) return;
        const mapX = Math.min(worldX * this.mapScale, this.mapWidth - Minimap.DOT_SIZE);
        const mapY = Math.min(worldY * this.mapScale, this.mapHeight - Minimap.DOT_SIZE);
        this.dots[index].setPosition(mapX, mapY);
    }
}

// Usage:
const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
const minimap = new Minimap(120, 90, 2400);
const node = minimap.getNode();
node.setPosition(winSize.width - 130, winSize.height - 100);
this.addChild(node, 50);

const playerDot = minimap.addEntity(100, 200, cc.color(0, 255, 0, 255));
const enemyDot = minimap.addEntity(500, 300, cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255));
minimap.updateEntity(playerDot, 150, 220);
```

The minimap background is a semi-transparent `cc.LayerColor`. Each entity is a small colored `cc.LayerColor` dot positioned by scaling world coordinates. `addEntity` returns an index for `updateEntity` to move dots as entities move in the world.

The `segments` parameter controls how many straight-line segments are used to approximate a curve. Curves in DrawNode (bezier, spline, circle) are not true curves — they are polygonal approximations.

**How it works:**
- The curve is divided into `segments` equal pieces
- Each piece is drawn as a straight line between calculated points
- More segments = smoother curve but more vertices = more draw cost

**Practical values:**
- `8-16`: Acceptable for small curves or circles
- `24-32`: Good default for most use cases
- `48-64`: Very smooth, use for large prominent curves
- `100+`: Rarely needed, diminishing returns

Example comparison:
```typescript
const draw = new cc.DrawNode();
this.addChild(draw);

// Coarse (visible edges)
draw.drawCircle(cc.p(100, 160), 50, 0, 8, false, 2, cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255));

// Smooth
draw.drawCircle(cc.p(240, 160), 50, 0, 32, false, 2, cc.color(0, 255, 0, 255));

// Very smooth (overkill for this size)
draw.drawCircle(cc.p(380, 160), 50, 0, 64, false, 2, cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255));
```

The same applies to `drawCubicBezier`, `drawQuadBezier`, `drawCatmullRom`, and `drawCardinalSpline`.

```typescript
const a = cc.p(1, 0);  // right
const b = cc.p(0, 1);  // up

// Dot product
const dot: number = cc.pDot(a, b);  // 0 (perpendicular)

// Angle between two vectors (in radians)
const angle: number = cc.pAngle(a, b);  // ~1.5708 (PI/2 = 90 degrees)

// Practical: check if target is in front of player
const playerDir = cc.pNormalize(cc.p(1, 0)); // facing right
const toTarget = cc.pNormalize(cc.pSub(targetPos, playerPos));
const dotProduct = cc.pDot(playerDir, toTarget);
if (dotProduct > 0.5) {
    cc.log('Target is roughly in front (within ~60 degree cone)');
}

// Practical: angle between direction vectors
const angleDeg = cc.pAngle(playerDir, toTarget) * cc.DEG;
cc.log('Angle to target:', angleDeg, 'degrees');
```

Signatures:
```typescript
cc.pDot(v1: cc.Point, v2: cc.Point): number
cc.pAngle(a: cc.Point, b: cc.Point): number  // returns radians
```

