Track touch events on list items and swap positions on drop:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
lv.setItemsMargin(5);
lv.setPosition(50, 50);

function createItem(text: string): ccui.Layout {
    const item = new ccui.Layout();
    item.setSize(cc.size(280, 50));
    item.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
    item.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(60, 60, 80));
    item.setTouchEnabled(true);

    const label = new ccui.Text(text, 'Arial', 18);
    label.setPosition(140, 25);
    item.addChild(label);

    let dragStartY = 0;
    item.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
        if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_BEGAN) {
            dragStartY = sender.getWorldPosition().y;
            sender.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(100, 100, 140));
        } else if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED) {
            sender.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(60, 60, 80));
            const dragEndY = sender.getWorldPosition().y;
            const fromIdx = lv.getIndex(sender);
            const delta = Math.round((dragStartY - dragEndY) / 55);
            const toIdx = Math.max(0, Math.min(lv.getItemsCount() - 1, fromIdx + delta));
            if (fromIdx !== toIdx) {
                lv.removeItem(fromIdx);
                lv.insertCustomItem(sender, toIdx);
            }
        }
    }, this);

    return item;
}

['Item A', 'Item B', 'Item C', 'Item D'].forEach(t => lv.pushBackCustomItem(createItem(t)));
this.addChild(lv);
```

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this animation event handler:

```typescript
armature.animation.setMovementEventCallFunc((arm, movType, movId) => {
    if (movType === 'COMPLETE') {
        arm.animation.play('idle', 5, -1);
    }
});
```

output:
The bug is comparing `movType` to the string `'COMPLETE'` instead of the enum constant `ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE`. The `movType` parameter is a number, not a string.

Fixed code:
```typescript
armature.animation.setMovementEventCallFunc((arm, movType, movId) => {
    if (movType === ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE) {
        arm.animation.play('idle', 5, -1);
    }
});
```

The available constants are:
- `ccs.MovementEventType.START` — animation started
- `ccs.MovementEventType.COMPLETE` — animation finished (non-looping)
- `ccs.MovementEventType.LOOP_COMPLETE` — one loop iteration completed

```typescript
function moveToward(
    current: cc.Point,
    target: cc.Point,
    speed: number,
    dt: number
): cc.Point {
    const diff = cc.pSub(target, current);
    const dist = cc.pLength(diff);

    if (dist <= speed * dt) {
        return cc.p(target.x, target.y);
    }

    const dir = cc.pNormalize(diff);
    return cc.pAdd(current, cc.pMult(dir, speed * dt));
}

// Usage in update:
class Chaser extends cc.Node {
    private _speed: number = 200;
    private _target: cc.Point = cc.p(400, 300);

    update(dt: number): void {
        const current = this.getPosition();
        const newPos = moveToward(current, this._target, this._speed, dt);
        this.setPosition(newPos);

        // Rotate to face movement direction
        const dir = cc.pSub(this._target, current);
        if (cc.pLength(dir) > 1) {
            const angle = Math.atan2(dir.y, dir.x) * cc.DEG;
            this.setRotation(-angle);
        }
    }
}
```

Set a background image with Scale9 enabled to stretch/tile it:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(400, 300));
panel.setBackGroundImage('panel_bg_9slice.png');
panel.setBackGroundImageScale9Enabled(true);
panel.setBackGroundImageCapInsets(cc.rect(20, 20, 60, 60));
panel.setPosition(40, 10);
this.addChild(panel);
```

The cap insets `cc.rect(20, 20, 60, 60)` means:
- The 20px borders on each side are preserved
- The center 60x60 region stretches to fill the remaining space
- Corners remain at their original size

This is the standard technique for scalable dialog boxes and panel backgrounds in Cocos2d-x UI.

`cc.director.getWinSize()` returns `cc.Size`:

```typescript
const winSize: cc.Size = cc.director.getWinSize();
cc.log('Screen:', winSize.width, 'x', winSize.height);

// Center a node on screen
node.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);

// Shortcut: cc.winSize is the same thing
